# NOC Whisperer — Cursor Rules

This project is the NOC Whisperer — a multi-agent alert correlation system.

Before writing any code:
1. Read @CONTEXT.md for architecture, data structures, agent contracts, and design decisions
2. Read @EXECUTION_PLAN.md for today's specific task and acceptance test
3. Implement exactly what the session specifies — no more, no less

Coding standards:
- Python 3.11+ with full type hints on all functions
- Dataclasses for all data structures (no dicts passed between agents)
- Every class must have a docstring
- Every public method must have a docstring
- Use mock MCP tools during development — never assume live OTel stack is running
- Handle all external API calls with try/except — return [] on failure, never crash
- Load config from yaml files — never hardcode values
- Load API keys from .env — never hardcode credentials
- Never use datetime.utcnow() — it is deprecated in Python 3.11+.
  Always use datetime.now(timezone.utc) instead.
  Ensure timezone is imported: from datetime import datetime, timezone

Testing:
- Every session ends with the acceptance test passing
- Run: python -c "from module import Class; print('OK')" as minimum smoke test
- Use in-memory SQLite (:memory:) for all incident store tests
- Always run pytest using the project venv:
  .venv/bin/python3 -m pytest tests/ -v
- Never use system python3 directly for pytest.
- Tests must never generate full production datasets.
- Use minimum data size that validates the logic:
  - Dataset generation tests: 3/2/1 incidents maximum
  - SFT preparation tests: 5 examples maximum
  - Training script tests: import and config validation only
- Full production runs happen via direct script execution only,
  never via pytest.
- For every MCP tool implementation, tests must include
  at least one test that calls the internal _to_canonical()
  or equivalent conversion method directly with a mock
  API response payload. This verifies the success path
  without requiring a live connection.

General rules:
- All file edits including .cursorrules must be driven
  through Cursor. Never edit files manually outside Cursor.

One file per session — do not create files not listed in the current session task.

Never suggest installing torch, transformers, peft, trl, or bitsandbytes
on the local development machine. These are GPU cluster only dependencies
defined in requirements-gpu.txt.

CONTEXT.md and EXECUTION_PLAN.md are read-only during all implementation
sessions. Never modify these files when writing code. If you find a gap
or error in either file, report it as a comment in your response only.
Only modify these files when explicitly asked with the instruction:
"Update CONTEXT.md" or "Update EXECUTION_PLAN.md".

Every session that creates a new Python module must also create
a corresponding test file in tests/test_<module_name>.py
The test file must cover:
  - Valid creation of all classes
  - Invalid inputs that should raise ValueError
  - Round-trip serialization if to_dict/from_dict exist
  - The session acceptance test converted to pytest format

Every session that creates implementation files must also
create a corresponding test file in tests/test_<module>.py.
The test file must always be listed explicitly in the
"Files to create" section of the session prompt.
If the user does not mention a test file, ask before proceeding.

At the start of every session, check docs/REMINDERS.md.
If any OPEN reminder is marked BLOCKING for the current
session number, alert the user immediately before writing
any code. Show the full reminder text and ask the user
to confirm it is resolved before proceeding.

All GPU training scripts must follow these requirements
learned from train_normalizer_sft.py debugging:

1. Load model with 4-bit quantization:
   from transformers import BitsAndBytesConfig
   bnb_config = BitsAndBytesConfig(
       load_in_4bit=True,
       bnb_4bit_compute_dtype=torch.float16,
       bnb_4bit_use_double_quant=True,
       bnb_4bit_quant_type="nf4"
   )
   model = AutoModelForCausalLM.from_pretrained(
       MODEL_NAME,
       quantization_config=bnb_config,
       device_map="auto"
   )

2. Pre-format dataset before SFTTrainer:
   formatted_data = [
       {"text": f"{record['prompt']}\n{record['completion']}"}
       for record in raw_data
   ]
   train_dataset = Dataset.from_list(formatted_data)

3. SFTTrainer must NOT have these arguments:
   - formatting_func
   - dataset_text_field
   - completion_only_loss

4. SFTConfig must have:
   per_device_train_batch_size=1
   gradient_accumulation_steps=4
   dataset_text_field="text"  (or omit — default is "text")
   DO NOT set fp16=True — conflicts with 4-bit quant

5. Set at top of script after imports:
   os.environ["PYTORCH_CUDA_ALLOC_CONF"] = "expandable_segments:True"

6. Add Dataset import with fallback shim for Mac testing:
   try:
       from datasets import Dataset
   except Exception:
       class Dataset:
           @staticmethod
           def from_list(raw_data):
               return raw_data

7. GPU budget for RTX 4060 Ti 16GB:
   SFT jobs:  ~30-60 minutes
   RLVR jobs: ~60-90 minutes
   All jobs must be submitted as background processes

